^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Let's talk a bit about the bidding. Some people play gambling 3N with Hope's hand. Had Hope had one more diamond, she has a gambling 3N bid. A gambling 3N shows an 8-card solid minor. Some people play it shows nothing outside and seven-card solid minor, but, as usual, I am not that disciplined. If you are going to gamble, then gamble, otherwise don't play it, lol. A gambling 3N tends to show a solid minor worth 8 tricks. Some people do it with a solid 7 card minor and an outside Ace, but most do not. Basically, your hope is since you have 8 tricks partner has 1, and they can't run 5 tricks.|
PG| ***** 34 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, should Hope bid 3D over 1H? It's close. She has a six loser hand and a singleton in partner's suit. I would probably have reluctantly bid 2D, but 3 is certainly conceivable. Using Bergen's Starting Points she has 14 HCP + 3 length - 2 for dubious shortness, which gives her 15. If you use the Bergen point count, you need 17 to jump to 3, so she is short. That combined with her losing trick count of six, and shortness in hearts, says 2 is probably more prudent. |
PG| ***** 35 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|However, given she bid 3, Eddy has a clear 3N bid. He has all the suits stopped, and 10 HCP. In fact, if diamonds were 3-3 or the Jack dropped, 3N makes easily. It still has plays even with a 4-2 diamond break.|
