^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Okay, the bidding was fine. Hope is close to a 3N bid. She has 9 HCP and a point for length. But if you use Bergen adjusted HCP you need 26 at least for game. Since Kerrie could have 15 or a bad 16, it is still worth only a 2N bid. If her club suit was better, say KQ instead of K10, then she has a better case. But with only one high honor, I think 2N is more prudent.|
PG| ***** 53 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, one  important point. Kerrie and Hope play 4 way transfers usually and 2N in this case is supposed to be a transfer to diamonds. This is a good illustration of why I recommend against playing 4 way transfers, because it is real easy to forget. Having said that, given they play 4 way transfers Hope has to bid 2C followed by 2N to invite with her hand. That is how you do an invitational 2N playing 4 way transfers. Therefore, 2C does not guarantee a 4 card major if you play 4 way transfer.|
PG| ***** 54 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, if Eddy wants to get frisky, he could bid 2H--DONT. Given the vul and his excellent distribution, it would be an interesting bid. But, it is definitely frisky, and I  would not even consider it except at this vulnerability. I like modified DONT much better. Let me review modified DONT quickly.|
PG| ***** 55 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|In modified DONT, 2H bid, rather than showing hearts and spades, just shows hearts. The reason I like it better is that there are more single suited major hands than 2 suited major hands. So, you preempt the opponents more often when you have a single suited heart hand. To show hearts and spades in modified DONT, you double and then bid hearts over the forced 2C bid. Therefore, double in modified DONT either shows a single suited minor or both majors.|
