^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Okay, let's discuss the play here. Terry needed to form a plan. He can count 3 heart tricks most likely, and 1 club and he is likely to get 3 spades if he goes after spades right away, maybe even 4. So, as he did, he plays a spade at trick 3. I think Linda should take the Ace. The reason being, Terry should not have 3 spades, since he did not raise spades. Therefore Anna has Jxx or jxxx. In any case, ducking the Ace costs a trick in many cases. But once Linda ducks, Terry should continue his plan.|
PG| ***** 113 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|He should assume Anna has the Ace, and lead a spade planning on finessing East for the Jack. When East shows up with the Ace, the contract is cold. So, by coming up with a plan, Terry can easily make the hand. Planning is the most important part of declarer play. Don't just randomly play suits. Figure out which suits you need to play to take the number of tricks you need to make. Playing the hand is not about figuring out how to play each suit per se. It is about figuring out how to take the number of tricks you need to take.|
